# Typed Middleware Registry

Zintrust supports _typed middleware names_ so you can catch typos at compile-time instead of at runtime.

## Why

Routes attach middleware by name (string). By default that’s flexible, but also easy to mistype.

## Built-in registry

The default middleware key registry lives in `src/config/middleware.ts`:

- `MiddlewareKeys` is the canonical list of known keys.
- `MiddlewareKey = keyof typeof MiddlewareKeys` is the type.

## Using typed middleware in routes

Most router methods accept a generic for middleware name:

```ts
import type { MiddlewareKey } from '@config/middleware';
import { Router, type IRouter } from '@routing/Router';

export function registerRoutes(router: IRouter): void {
  Router.get<MiddlewareKey>(
    router,
    '/admin',
    async (_req, res) => {
      res.json({ ok: true });
    },
    {
      middleware: ['auth', 'jwt'],
    }
  );
}
```

If you try `middleware: ['autth']`, TypeScript will error.

## Extending the registry

In your app/project, add keys to the shared registry pattern (object + `keyof`). Keep the runtime registry (`middlewareConfig.route`) and the compile-time registry (`MiddlewareKey`) in sync.

## Notes

- The kernel resolves middleware names to actual functions via `middlewareConfig.route`.
- A typed registry prevents typos, but it won’t validate ordering or middleware behavior.
